{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":13884,"record_hash":"sha256:606f6841f636322555081d660f966071da74deebb7c79a3f9e6b7718190cbe6c","timestamp":"2026-05-09T17:27:00.833Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 455a3c\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 2117\nOutput:\n# GitMeta Data Model\n\n## Principles\n\n- Use GitMeta standard keys where they fit.\n- Use GitButler-specific keys only for capture bookkeeping.\n- Preserve transcript records as JSONL-compatible strings in local-only storage.\n- Use `git-meta-lib` as the storage abstraction; do not reimplement custom Git\n  metadata refs/branches in GitButler.\n- Avoid pretending a session belongs to a commit or branch when that is not\n  known.\n- Keep local capture cheap; serialize later at push/sync boundaries.\n- Prefer a conservative `project` target in the POC over misleading branch or\n  commit inference.\n\nGitMeta stores metadata as `(target, key, value)` tuples. Supported target types\ninclude `commit`, `change-id`, `branch`, `path`, and `project`. Keys are\nnamespace-like strings split on `:`, and list values are append-friendly logs.\n\n## Standard Agent Keys\n\nGitMeta recommends these agent keys:\n\n```text\nagent:provider\nagent:model\nagent:session-id\nagent:prompt\nagent:summary\nagent:transcript\n```\n\n`agent:transcript` is a list where each item is a JSONL record encoding a\nmessage, content, and tool calls. This is the likely future publishable/indexed\nformat, but it is not first-POC storage.\n\n## POC Storage Model\n\nFor the first implementation, write to `project` unless `--target` is explicit.\nDo not write publishable `agent:*` keys in the POC. Keep all captured state\nunder GitButler local-only keys until there is an explicit mapping and\npublication policy.\n\nMinimum useful writes:\n\n```text\nmeta:local:gitbutler:agent-session:<agent>:<session-key>:session-id = <session-key>\nmeta:local:gitbutler:agent-session:<agent>:<session-key>:source-path = <path>\nmeta:local:gitbutler:agent-session:<agent>:<session-key>:source-size = <decimal-bytes>\nmeta:local:gitbutler:agent-session:<agent>:<session-key>:source-sha256 = <hash>\nmeta:local:gitbutler:agent-session:<agent>:<session-key>:last-record-index = <decimal-index>\nmeta:local:gitbutler:agent\n[TRUNCATED]\n\n- a user-provided `--target commit:<sha>`\n\nDo not assume `HEAD` is the commit produced by the session.\n\n### Change-ID Target\n\nUse `change-id:<id>` if a future GitButler or Jujutsu integration exposes a\nstable change identity. This may become the strongest target for sessions that\nsurvive rebases.\n\n## Serialization\n\nCapture should update GitMeta local storage only. The first POC should not call\n`serialize()` at all.\n\nSerialization should happen during a GitButler push/sync integration once the\nproduct decides:\n\n- which metadata is shareable\n- which destination ref receives transcript data\n- what filters apply to private or sensitive keys\n- how failures are surfaced when code push succeeds but metadata push fails\n\nAn explicit debug flag like `--serialize` may be useful for later development,\nbut it is not part of the first POC.\n\nBefore any transcript data is serialized, synced, pushed, or moved out of\n`meta:local:*`, require an explicit publication policy. Keep that out of the POC.\n\n## Redaction and Filters\n\nThe first implementation preserves transcript envelopes locally on every\ncapture. Stored copied envelope strings and `source_record` string values pass\nthrough a small redaction guard for generic sensitive field names, high-entropy\nstrings, UUID-shaped values, and random-looking long hex strings first. The POC\nintentionally avoids schema-specific allowlists for paths, Git hashes, or\nprovider IDs. Publication requires a stronger policy.\n\nPotential future rules:\n\n- store hashes, summaries, and cursor metadata before storing full transcript\n  content\n- route transcript keys to a private metadata destination\n- keep raw POC transcripts in `meta:local:*`; do not write publishable\n  `agent:transcript` until a publication policy exists\n- make `source-path`, `cwd`, record hashes, and raw transcript keys\n  private/local-only until a push policy exists\n- expand redaction beyond the POC field-name/entropy/hex guard\n- support per-repository capture settings\n- support user confirmation before enabling remote exchange\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-09T17:27:00.833Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}